  "prompt": "How dangerous are corn snakes, and are they venomous?",
  "response": "Corn snakes (Pantherophis guttatus) are generally not dangerous and are considered harmless to humans. They are non-venomous and are typically quite docile, making them popular pets. Corn snakes are known for their manageable size, usually growing to about 2 to 6 feet in length, and their striking coloration.\n\nThey primarily feed on small rodents, birds, and other small animals in their natural habitat. When threatened, they may bite, but their bites are typically more surprising than harmful. With proper handling and care, corn snakes are not aggressive. Always ensure to research and understand the needs and behaviors of any pet snake before acquiring one to ensure both the snake's well-being and safety for any handlers.",
